   How to start? Fermilab Workshop on Physics at the First Muon Collider
   and at the Front End of a Muon Collider ¶ A First Muon Collider? *
   high-luminosity Z factory * Higgs factory * W +W - threshold * t¯t
   threshold * s 1 TeV to explore SUSY or Techni world 2 ¶ Front-end
   physics * intense low-energy hadron beams * a copious source of
   low-energy muons * intense µ and ¯ e or ¯ µ and e beams W&C C. Quigg,
   "Physics Opportunities in Fermilab's Futures" 29 45 The Front End * A
   high-intensity proton source. CDR by 1/1/2001: Weiren Chou, et al. * A
   system for pion production, collection, and decay to capture about 1.5
   × 1021 µ+ and µ- per year. * A muon cooling channel to concentrate the
   muons in six-dimensional phase space. * A muon acceleration system to
   raise the captured muons quickly to the desired energy. W&C C. Quigg,
   "Physics Opportunities in Fermilab's Futures" 30 45 Higgs Factory at s
   = MH If Higgs is light (MH < 2MW ) and narrow, µ+µ- H b¯b and other
   modes may allow a comprehensive study of Higgs properties. Assume Higgs
   discovered and MH = (100 - 200) MeV/c2. * modest luminosity (0.05
   fb-1/year) and high momentum resolution ( p/p = 3 × 10-5): s a few MeV
   (H all). * standard luminosity (0.6 fb-1/year) and momentum resolution
   ( p/p = 10-3): s (H all). Two-phase study: 1. Determine mass with MH s
   2 MeV/c2. Requires 0.15 fb-1, about three nominal years. 2. Scan at s =
   MH, MH ± s to determine MH 0.1 MeV/c2, H 0.5 MeV 16 H, ( · B(H b¯b))
   3%, and ( · B(H W W )) 15%. Requires 8 years to accumulate 0.40 fb-1.
   Unparalleled measurements, luminosity at a premium. W&C C. Quigg,
   "Physics Opportunities in Fermilab's Futures" 31 45 Neutrino Beams from
   Stored Muons Neutrino beam generated in µ- e- µ¯ e contains µ and ¯ e,
   but no ¯ µ, e, , or ¯ . Muon charge, momentum, polarization determine
   composition and spectrum of the neutrino beam. ¶ New element: storing a
   millimole of muons per year, giving intense beams for * Oscillation
   studies over a wide range of distance/energy and at very great
   distances * Deeply inelastic scattering on thin targets Requires less
   development of cooling technology than a muon collider. W&C C. Quigg,
   "Physics Opportunities in Fermilab's Futures" 32 45 Long-Baseline
